#   SUBS-010: stale "git source needs `--sub`" gating in comments and the test shim (LANDED)

**LOW — LANDED `cda5c691` (2026-06-06).**  The `--sub`-appending shim was
removed from `test/lib/submodules.sh` and `test/lib/sub-deep.sh` (tests now
drive default recursion via the real binary), and the stale "POST-001 phase 2 /
does NOT recurse by default" narrative was purged from get/05, get/32, get/37,
post/15, and `beagle/test/be-post-nosub.sh` (redundant `--sub` tokens dropped).
`rg` confirms no remaining stale narrative; affected test surface stays green.

**LOW (docs / test hygiene).**  Recursion is now default-on for every source
type, including git/ssh: there is no `CLIHas(c,"--sub")` anywhere in the code,
only six `--nosub` opt-out sites in `beagle/BE.cli.c` (head 741, get 871, patch
1007, post 2234/2310, relay 2501).  Several comments and one test shim still
describe the removed "POST-001 phase 2" rule that a git/ssh parent does NOT
recurse by default and must opt in with `--sub`.  This is misleading and the
`--sub` shim masks the real default behavior under test.

##  Stale spots
 -  `test/lib/submodules.sh` wraps `$BE` in a shim that appends `--sub` to
    every call (lines ~40-58), with a comment claiming git parents need it.
    `--sub` is a dead no-op, so the shim is harmless but masks default-recursion
    coverage — tests that mean to assert DEFAULT behavior should use
    `$REAL_BE`.
 -  `test/get/05-submodule-from-ssh` and `test/get/07-submodule-nosub` header
    comments describe the `--sub` opt-in as load-bearing.
 -  Any `POST-001` / "phase 2" / "does NOT recurse by default" comments
    referencing the git-source gate.

##  Action
 -  Remove the `--sub`-appending shim (or keep it only where a case explicitly
    wants the no-op flag exercised); default new tests to `$REAL_BE`.
 -  Update the get/05,07 and submodules.sh comments to state the current rule:
    recursion default-on for all sources, `--nosub` the only opt-out, `--sub`
    a tolerated no-op.
 -  Optionally drop the `--sub` token entirely if no longer wanted as an
    explicit no-op.

##  Notes
Not a correctness bug — behavior already matches the desired
"`--sub` = default, suppressed by `--nosub`" directive.  This ticket is purely
to remove the stale narrative so future readers are not misled.

